[1] England: alert
Date: Wed 6 Jun 2018, 8:41 AM
Source: Devon Live [edited]
https://www.devonlive.com/news/devon-news/measles-outbreak-warning-letters-being-1644268


Parents in Devon are being sent home a letter warning of an ongoing outbreak of measles. Public Health England (PHE) have confirmed there have been 71 cases in the South West this year [2018] following an increase in cases throughout England and Europe. So far the local measles cases have centred on Bristol, North Somerset and South Gloucestershire. It means unimmunised individuals will be at a real increased risk of contracting the infection.

In the letter parents are being asked for their support in raising awareness of measles and to get their children vaccinated with the MMR [measles, mumps and rubella] vaccine. Among the Devon schools to have sent the letter out is Torquay Grammar School, but PHE have confirmed there have been no reported cases of measles recently in the Torbay or Devon area. There have been no confirmed cases in Devon this year [2018].

A spokesperson for PHE said: "The letters have been issued to provide information about the increase in cases across the UK and Europe to make people aware of symptoms, especially if they are travelling this summer, to check their vaccination status, and ensure they are up to date with their MMR vaccination. It also states the importance of exclusion if people suspect that they have measles - for example, not attending nursery, school, work, large events etc if you are symptomatic. We also advise to contact health services ahead if you are planning to attend GP practices etc so not to potentially infect others if you do have symptoms."

[byline: Anita Merritt]

