[5] Venezuela
Date: Thu 7 Jun 2018
Source: Efecto Cocuyo [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
http://efectococuyo.com/salud/fallece-bebe-de-seis-meses-con-sospecha-de-sarampion-en-hospital-j-m-de-los-rios/


A 6 month old child died at the pediatric hospital José Manuel de los Ríos the afternoon of last [Mon 4 Jun 2018]. The child entered the pediatric intensive care unit of the health center [Sat 2 Jun 2018] with respiratory complications and suspected measles.

Efecto Cocuyo understands that the baby died from septic shock resulting from bilateral pneumonia. The baby was born in Trujillo state and his family is resident in the Andean region. It is believed that the respiratory complications were secondary to measles because the child arrived with red spots on the skin, but doctors indicated that it was not possible to confirm the diagnosis of measles because the symptoms were "residual": the exanthema (rash) was disappearing. Nor were specimens taken to make the confirmatory tests.

This would be the 4th death due to measles in José Manuel de los Ríos in one year. The 1st to die was a 1 year old girl from Catia, who died on [8 Feb 2018]. She developed pneumonia, the commonest cause of death associated with measles in infants. Two other deaths, both in children of nursing age [presumably infancy. - Mod.SH] were recorded early in May, one on Sat 5 May 2018 and another on Mon 7 May 2018. The patients were treated in the emergency and in the pediatric intensive care unit of the hospital and presented with respiratory complications.

According to the latest epidemiological bulletin of the Pan American Health Organization, released on [Fri 8 May 2018], the agency reported 2 deaths from measles and 1631 confirmed cases of viral infection in Venezuela since mid-2017.

[byline: Julett Pineda Sleinan]

