[7] India (Churachandpur)
Date: Fri 8 Jun 2018
Source: The Sangai Express /DIO [edited]
http://e-pao.net/GP.asp?src=16..090618.jun18


Measles broke out at Monglenphai and K Sinai village which are located close to Churachandpur district headquarters on [Tue 5 Jun 2018], informed a source. Even though it is said that the outbreak is confined within the 2 villages, the Churachandpur chief medical officer (CMO) today [Fri 8 Jun 2018] submitted a report to the health department.

A 4year old girl died at K Sinai village due to measles in the night of [Tue 5 Jun 2018]. K Sinai village is located about 3 to 4 km [approx 1.8 to 2.5 mi] away from Churachandpur District Hospital. Measles outbreak has also been reported at Monglenphai village under Leisang PHSC of Samulamlan Block.

Dr Jam Thianlal, district family welfare officer [DFWO], Churachandpur issued an outbreak notification on [Wed 6 Jun 2018]. After they were informed about the outbreak by officials of the health department, officials of WHO went to the 2 villages and collected blood samples. They have sent the blood samples to the WHO accredited laboratory located at Guwahati. Medical teams have been sent to both villages to vaccinate children against measles and rubella who missed such vaccination camps held earlier.

Meanwhile, additional director, FWS [family welfare service? - Mod.SH] and state observer (Churachandpur district) of the measles-rubella campaign Dr Th Somorendra Singh rushed to the villages today [Fri 8 Jun 2018] to collect a report of the outbreak at the instruction of the state immunisation officer (SIO). He said that the outbreak was due to resistance by the villagers to the vaccination campaign.

DFWO, Churachandpur has sent measles outbreak report in the district to the director of Health and Family Welfare today [Fri 8 Jun 2018] besides holding an awareness campaign at vulnerable locations since yesterday [Thu 7 Jun 2018]. At the same time, a team comprised of staff from the District Surveillance Office, DFWO and ASHA [? - Mod.SH] Monglenphai collected and sent for laboratory examinations, blood samples and throat swabs of the victims.

Dr Jam Thianlal said, "The victims (of these 2 villages) are found to be resistant families to vaccination during the 2 rounds of Outreach Sessions and 1 round of school session held earlier." Dr Jam Thianlal cautioned that the outbreak can continue since there are some villages which resisted MR vaccination and awareness campaign which was launched in the district since March this year [2018]. He urged all concerned to vaccinate their children aged between 9 months and 15 years, against measles and rubella at the district immunisation office or any nearest public health clinics, which can be done every day.

If all children are vaccinated, the disease would be prevented and the case might be eliminated in the entire state within 2 years, the DWFO said. Dr Th Somorendra Singh urged the people not to panic but vaccinate their children at the earliest.

